'''Bellsybabble''' is a fictional language of the [[Devil]], which he makes up as he goes along. Writer [[James Joyce]] mentions it in the following postscript to a letter (containing the story now known as "The Cat and the Devil"), which he wrote  in 1936<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Cambridge University Press| isbn = 978-1-139-43523-9| last = Milesi| first = Laurent| title = James Joyce and the Difference of Language| date = 2003-07-24| url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=eRonW7lL64MC| p=60}}</ref> to his four-year-old [[Stephen James Joyce|grandson]]:<ref name="Melchiori1988">{{Cite book| publisher = John Benjamins Publishing| editors = Rosa Maria Bollettieri Bosinelli, Carla Marengo, Christine van Boheemen (eds.)| last = Melchiori| first = Giorgio| author-link=Giorgio Melchiori|title = The Languages of Joyce: Selected Papers from the 11th International James Joyce Symposium Venice 1988| chapter = The Languages of Joyce| date = 1992}}</ref>{{rp|15–16}}
{{quote|The devil mostly speaks a language of his own called Bellsybabble which he makes up himself as he goes along but when he is very angry he can speak quite bad French very well though some who have heard him say that he has a strong Dublin accent.}}

The name "Bellsybabble" is a [[pun]] on [[Beelzebub]], [[:wikt:babble|"babble"]] and [[Tower of Babel|Babel]]. Bellsybabble has variously been called a poly-language,<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 0885-0429| volume = 32| issue = 4| pages = 354–367| last = Hodgkins| first = Hope Howell| title = High Modernism for the Lowest: Children's Books by Woolf, Joyce, and Greene| journal = Children's Literature Association Quarterly| accessdate = 2016-05-17| date = 2007| url = http://search.proquest.com/docview/232430503/abstract/96D42492A5FF4B7FPQ/6}}</ref> a pluridialectal idiom<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 19| issue = 2| pages = 343–374, 483, 487–488| last = Mihálycsa| first = Erika| title = "Writing to the self-accompaniment of a tongue that is not mine": The Figure of Translation in Beckett's Work| journal = HJEAS : Hungarian Journal of English and American Studies| accessdate = 2016-05-17| date = 2013| url = http://search.proquest.com/docview/1664902206/citation/96D42492A5FF4B7FPQ/5}}</ref> and a ludic creation.<ref>{{Cite journal| volume = 19| pages = 35–44| last = Cronin| first = Michael| title = After Bellsybabble: Transformation, Invention, and Resistance in Translation| journal = Parallèles| date = 1998}}</ref>{{rp|35}}

== Significance ==
For [[Giorgio Melchiori]], it is suggestive of the idea that in [[literary text]]s, there is not a single language, but a multitude of languages, a different one for each reader of the text.<ref name="Melchiori1988"/>{{rp|16}} It has been compared with the language of Joyce's novel ''[[Finnegans Wake]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal| publisher = Emory University| last = Ferris| first = Kathleen Richard| title = James Joyce, Wandering Jew| location = United States -- Georgia| accessdate = 2016-05-17| date = 1989| url = http://search.proquest.com/docview/303794530/abstract/CE031289D61944E4PQ/7|p=60}}</ref> and has also provided the inspiration for [[C. George Sandulescu]]'s study of ''Finnegans Wake'', entitled ''The Language of the Devil''.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = C. Smythe| isbn = 978-0-8023-1284-6| last = Sandulescu| first = Constantin-George| title = The language of the Devil : texture and archetype in Finnegans wake| location = Gerrards Cross, Buckinghamshire| date = 1988}}</ref>{{rp|vi}}

Linguist [[John Haiman (linguist)|John Haiman]] compares Bellsybabble to ordinary [[language]] in the way it continually shapes, and is in turn shaped by, the utterances spoken within it.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press| isbn = 978-0-19-511524-6| last = Haiman| first = John| title = Talk is cheap : sarcasm, alienation, and the evolution of language| location = Oxford| date = 1998}}</ref>{{rp|178}} This challenges the rigid [[Langue and parole|separation]] between [[Linguistic competence|code]] and [[linguistic performance|message]]. On one hand, the language determines the presupposed content and boundaries of possible messages, as shown by the concept of [[linguistic relativity]]. On the other hand, the message may also affect the code used by that very message.<ref>In English, this can happen in sentences of the type "A is B", where "A" differs from "B" in person or number. Here the grammatical pattern that requires a verb to [[Grammatical agreement|agree]] with its subject can give way, allowing agreement with whatever is asserted to be identical to the subject. Thus in the sentence "[[Our Father]], who ''are'' in heaven," it is only the use of "Our Father" as a term of address that allows the verb "are" to be in the second person. (Haiman 1998, p. 177)</ref>

